👉 Java Finally Block

The finally block is used with try-catch and it always executes, no matter what happens.

Whether:

Exception occurs 
Exception does NOT occur

Syntax :

try {
    // risky code
} catch (Exception e) {
    // handle exception
} finally {
    // always runs
}

1. finally always executes
2. Used for cleanup work
3. Runs even if:
   (a) return is used
   (b) exception occurs or not
4. Common uses:
   (a) Closing files 
   (b) Closing database connections 
   (c) Releasing resources

👉 Sample Code :

class TestFinally {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            int a = 10 / 0;   // Exception
        } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
            System.out.println("Exception caught");
        } finally {
            System.out.println("This always runs");
        }
    }
}

Output :

Exception caught
This always runs

👉 Example WITHOUT Exception

try {
    int a = 10 / 2;   // No exception
    System.out.println(a);
} finally {
    System.out.println("This still runs");
}

Output :

5
This still runs


👉 When finally may NOT run

Very rare cases:
                System crash
                System.exit() is called
